    "question_id": "MH_011",
    "question": "How do Gaussian processes and Bayesian personalized ranking utilize log-likelihood, and why is it advantageous to use log-likelihood in these models?",
    "gold_answer": "Gaussian processes and Bayesian personalized ranking both leverage the concept of log-likelihood to handle complexities in their probabilistic models. In Gaussian processes, log-likelihood allows for exact Bayesian inference in closed form, providing a practical way to handle predictions and uncertainty, especially when dealing with kernel hyperparameters. Bayesian personalized ranking uses log-likelihood to maximize posterior probability, turning the ranking task into a manageable optimization problem. Log-likelihood simplifies computation by converting products of probabilities into sums, which is crucial in dealing with large datasets or when probabilities are very small, as seen in log transformations. This approach is also used in numerical optimization to ensure calculations remain within machine precision limits.",
