    "question_id": "MH_012",
    "question": "How do different neural network architectures address the challenges of symmetry, non-linearity, and conditional independence in classification and prediction tasks?",
    "gold_answer": "Neural networks, such as linear models, multilayer perceptrons (MLPs), and AutoRec, address various challenges through their architectures. Linear models use affine functions to estimate conditional probabilities, but they may struggle with capturing complex relationships due to their linear nature. MLPs introduce hidden layers to break symmetry issues by using different weights and biases, ensuring diverse activations from hidden units. AutoRec, a nonlinear model, uses autoencoder architecture to capture intricate user preferences in collaborative filtering tasks, overcoming the limitations of linear models. Meanwhile, the Naive Bayes classifier introduces conditional independence assumptions to simplify probability calculations, while recurrent neural networks (RNNs) use truncated backpropagation through time to focus on short-term dependencies, balancing complexity and stability.",
