    "question": "How do the training procedures and data processing techniques for convolutional neural networks like VGG and GoogleNet compare to those used in natural language processing tasks such as pretraining BERT with the Penn Tree Bank dataset?",
    "gold_answer": "Training convolutional neural networks like VGG and GoogleNet involves specific architectural choices and data preprocessing steps, such as resizing Fashion-MNIST images to different resolutions (224x224 for VGG and 96x96 for GoogleNet) and utilizing a learning rate of 0.01. In contrast, natural language processing tasks, such as pretraining BERT, use the Penn Tree Bank dataset, which involves tokenizing words, building a vocabulary with a minimum frequency threshold, and handling rare words with an <unk> token. Pretraining BERT also involves tasks like masked language modeling and next sentence prediction, which are evaluated through loss metrics. The data processing for PTB includes subsampling sentences and creating data iterators, highlighting the differences in data handling between image-based and text-based models.",
