    "question": "How do different deep learning models handle training with respect to batch size, learning rate, and computational resources, and what are the commonalities and differences in their training workflows?",
    "gold_answer": "Training deep learning models involves various strategies for optimizing batch size, learning rate, and computational resources. In convolutional networks like DenseNet and LeNet, reducing input dimensions can simplify computations, and hyperparameter optimization techniques like random search can fine-tune batch size and learning rate for better performance. For sequence models, such as those using attention mechanisms in Seq2Seq, training involves setting specific hyperparameters like embedding size and dropout, and managing resources with gradient clipping. Meanwhile, multilayer perceptrons (MLPs) and recurrent models like GRUs maintain similar training loops to simpler models like softmax regression, emphasizing consistency across different architectures. Despite these differences, the overarching workflow of defining models, data, and trainers, and then fitting the model, remains a commonality across all these frameworks.",
