    "question": "How do the computational challenges of exhaustive search in sequence prediction relate to optimization techniques for minimizing loss in machine learning models?",
    "gold_answer": "Exhaustive search in sequence prediction involves evaluating an extremely large number of possible sequences, which becomes computationally infeasible due to its exponential complexity with respect to sequence length and vocabulary size. This situation is akin to the challenges faced in hyperparameter optimization, where random search is preferred over grid search to mitigate the curse of dimensionality. Both scenarios highlight the need for efficient search and optimization strategies. In machine learning, gradient descent is employed to iteratively adjust model parameters to minimize loss, leveraging automatic differentiation to compute gradients efficiently. These gradients are crucial for navigating the parameter space, similar to how random search explores hyperparameter configurations. Thus, both sequence prediction and model optimization require balancing computational feasibility with the pursuit of optimal solutions.",
