    "question_id": "MH_035",
    "question": "How do the concepts of connectivity and attention patterns differ between DenseNet and BERT, and how do these differences impact their respective implementations in deep learning frameworks?",
    "gold_answer": "DenseNet and BERT differ significantly in their connectivity and attention mechanisms, which influence their implementations. DenseNet uses a connectivity pattern where each layer connects to all preceding layers, utilizing concatenation to preserve features, which is distinct from the residual connections in ResNet. This connectivity pattern requires careful implementation to manage the flow of information through multiple layers. In contrast, BERT employs a Transformer encoder with a masked language modeling approach, allowing each token to attend to all others in the sequence, which is facilitated by a bidirectional attention mechanism. This attention pattern in BERT requires a more complex implementation to handle the dynamic attention weights across tokens. Implementing these architectures in deep learning frameworks like PyTorch or TensorFlow involves utilizing specific classes and methods to handle these unique connectivity and attention patterns.",
