    "question": "How do modern language models leverage pretraining and fine-tuning techniques to improve performance on natural language processing tasks, and what roles do architectures like RNNs and Transformers play in this process?",
    "gold_answer": "Modern language models improve performance on NLP tasks by leveraging pretraining and fine-tuning techniques, which are crucial for handling complex language understanding and generation tasks. Pretraining, as seen in BERT, involves tasks like masked language modeling and next sentence prediction, providing a robust base of language understanding. Fine-tuning, such as with T5, involves adapting these pretrained models to specific tasks using task descriptions and sequence generation capabilities. RNNs and attention mechanisms are foundational in these architectures, with RNNs being used for sequence modeling and Transformers enhancing this with self-attention for better handling of dependencies in text. These models are then scaled up with more data and compute, forming the basis for state-of-the-art systems across diverse NLP applications.",
