    "question": "How do different neural network architectures handle sequence data, and what are the implications for training and model customization?",
    "gold_answer": "Neural network architectures such as RNNs and Transformers handle sequence data differently, impacting training and customization. RNNs, as described in the encoder section, transform variable-length input sequences into fixed-shape context variables using recurrent layers, which can be customized for specific tasks. Transformers, on the other hand, utilize self-attention mechanisms and positional encoding to manage sequences, enabling parallel processing and often resulting in more efficient training. This is exemplified in the training of models like ResNet, where the architecture's flexibility necessitates more training data to close the gap between training and validation loss. Implementing models from scratch, as in linear regression, provides deeper insights into how these components work, which is crucial for effective customization. Additionally, utility functions like sequence masking and masked softmax cross-entropy loss are essential for handling sequence data, ensuring that irrelevant parts of the sequence do not affect the loss computation.",
