    "question_id": "MH_041",
    "question": "How does the implementation of a multilayer RNN from scratch integrate concepts of backpropagation and stochastic gradient descent to optimize the parameters, and what challenges arise in ensuring accurate predictions on unseen data?",
    "gold_answer": "The implementation of a multilayer RNN from scratch involves treating each layer as an independent RNN with its own learnable parameters, which are optimized using backpropagation. Backpropagation calculates the gradients of the loss function with respect to each parameter by propagating errors backward through the network, as described in the context of higher-dimensional differentiation. This process is combined with stochastic gradient descent, where parameters are updated using randomly chosen minibatches, introducing non-determinism and potentially leading to convergence issues. The challenge lies in not only minimizing the loss on the training data but also ensuring that the learned parameters generalize well to unseen data, a common difficulty in deep learning due to the complex loss surfaces and the presence of many saddle points and minima.",
    "gold_chunk_ids": [
