    "question_id": "MH_047",
    "question": "How do different neural network architectures handle activation functions and pooling layers, and what are the implications for model complexity and performance?",
    "gold_answer": "Neural network architectures like LeNet and ResNet-18 employ different strategies for activation functions and pooling layers, reflecting their design philosophies and performance goals. LeNet, as applied to Fashion-MNIST, uses ReLU activation and MaxPooling to reduce computational load while maintaining performance. In contrast, a modified ResNet-18 variant omits MaxPooling in the initial layers and employs a smaller convolution kernel, emphasizing detailed feature extraction. The use of leaky ReLU in GAN discriminators addresses the 'dying ReLU' problem, ensuring neurons can learn even when they output negative values. Downsampling blocks, similar to VGG designs, use MaxPooling to adjust feature map scales, enhancing receptive fields. These architectural choices, supported by predefined layers in frameworks, balance complexity and efficiency, facilitating scalable model development.",
